const replacements = [
  // === AYN RAND ===
  // 1. Rational Self-Interest
  {
    find: `philosophical justification for productive ambition." },\n     { title:"The Virtue of Productive Achievement"`,
    replace: `philosophical justification for productive ambition.",
       expanded:"To understand Rand's ethics, it helps to know what she was reacting against. Born Alisa Rosenbaum in St. Petersburg in 1905, Rand lived through the Russian Revolution as a teenager. She watched the Bolsheviks confiscate her father's pharmacy, saw her family reduced to poverty, and experienced firsthand a regime that demanded sacrifice of the individual to the collective. When she arrived in the United States in 1926, she carried an intense conviction that any moral system demanding self-sacrifice was not just wrong but dangerous — a philosophical weapon used by the strong to exploit the productive.\\n\\nRand's ethical argument has a specific logical structure. She begins with a metaethical question: why do living organisms need values at all? Her answer is that only living things face the alternative of existence or non-existence. A rock has no values because nothing can threaten or benefit it. A plant 'values' sunlight and water in the sense that it needs them to survive. A human being, uniquely, must choose to identify and pursue the values that sustain life — and reason is the faculty by which this identification is made. From this biological starting point, Rand derives the claim that the standard of moral value is the individual's own life and that the virtue of selfishness is the commitment to thinking and acting for the sake of one's own rational flourishing.\\n\\nThe philosophical objections are numerous and well-documented. Critics like Robert Nozick (himself a libertarian) pointed out that Rand's derivation of values from the requirements of survival involves a subtle equivocation: the life that serves as the standard of value shifts between mere biological survival and a flourishing, ambitious, creative life. A hermit eating berries satisfies the survival criterion, but Rand clearly has something much richer in mind. Kantians object that Rand's ethics reduces other people to instruments of one's own happiness. Virtue ethicists in the Aristotelian tradition — to whom Rand claimed affinity — note that Aristotle considered generosity, friendship, and civic participation essential virtues, not optional extras.\\n\\nRand's response to the charge of atomistic selfishness was more nuanced than critics often acknowledge. She distinguished sharply between the 'selfishness' she defended — the rational pursuit of objective values including love, friendship, and honest dealing — and the caricature of selfishness as predatory exploitation. In her ethics, a con artist is not selfish but self-destructive, because he substitutes manipulation for productive achievement and thereby undermines the rational faculty on which his life depends. The trader, who deals with others by voluntary exchange of value for value, is Rand's model of proper human relationships.\\n\\nWhatever the philosophical merits of her arguments, Rand's cultural influence is difficult to ignore. Surveys have consistently ranked Atlas Shrugged among the books Americans say have most influenced their lives. Silicon Valley entrepreneurs, Federal Reserve chairs (Alan Greenspan was a member of Rand's inner circle), and Supreme Court justices have cited her work. The gap between her near-total rejection by academic philosophy and her enormous influence on American culture is itself an interesting sociological phenomenon — a case study in how philosophical ideas spread through literature rather than through peer-reviewed journals." },
     { title:"The Virtue of Productive Achievement"`
  },
  // 2. Virtue of Productive Achievement
  {
    find: `productive work is central to human dignity." },\n     { title:"Individual Rights as Moral Absolutes"`,
    replace: `productive work is central to human dignity.",
       expanded:"Rand's celebration of the creator-hero needs to be placed in historical context. She wrote The Fountainhead during World War II and Atlas Shrugged during the early Cold War — a period when collectivism in various forms (Soviet communism, European social democracy, American New Deal liberalism) dominated political thought. The prevailing intellectual mood held that individual ambition was suspect, that the businessman was at best a necessary evil, and that the proper role of the talented individual was service to society. Rand set out to reverse this entire moral framework.\\n\\nHoward Roark, the architect-hero of The Fountainhead, is her first sustained portrait of the ideal creator. Roark designs buildings according to his own vision, refuses to compromise with clients or committees who want conventional designs, and would rather work in a quarry than produce mediocre architecture. When a public housing project he designed is altered without his consent, he dynamites it — and the novel asks the reader to see this as a heroic act, the defense of creative integrity against collective mediocrity. The philosophical point is that creative work is not a commodity to be shaped by democratic consensus; it is the expression of an individual mind, and diluting it to satisfy the crowd destroys its value.\\n\\nIn Atlas Shrugged, Rand extended this argument to the entire economy. The novel's central conceit — a strike of the creative minds, who withdraw their productive ability from a society that exploits and condemns them — dramatizes Rand's claim that creators and producers are the real benefactors of civilization, not its parasites. When John Galt and his fellow strikers disappear, the economy collapses, demonstrating (in Rand's fiction) that the world depends on the very people it most resents.\\n\\nThe philosophical weakness in Rand's account of productive achievement is her tendency to treat creation as a solitary act. Real innovation is almost always collaborative: the Manhattan Project, the development of the internet, the Human Genome Project, and the founding of most successful companies involved teams, institutions, and accumulated knowledge. Rand's fictional heroes work essentially alone, which makes for compelling drama but questionable sociology. Her account of productive genius also struggles with the role of luck, inherited advantage, and the social infrastructure (education, legal systems, public research) that makes individual achievement possible.\\n\\nDespite these limitations, Rand identified something that mainstream philosophy had largely neglected: the moral significance of productive work. Most ethical theories treat work as a means to other ends — happiness, duty, social welfare — rather than as a central human good in its own right. Rand's insistence that the act of creating value through rational effort is itself a moral achievement, not just an economic one, resonated with millions of readers who experienced their own work as a source of meaning and identity rather than mere labor." },
     { title:"Individual Rights as Moral Absolutes"`
  },
  // 3. Individual Rights as Moral Absolutes
  {
    find: `Atlas Shrugged remains one of the most widely read and discussed novels in American culture." }],`,
    replace: `Atlas Shrugged remains one of the most widely read and discussed novels in American culture.",
       expanded:"Rand's theory of rights draws on the natural rights tradition of John Locke but pushes it in a more radical direction. Locke grounded natural rights in God's creation of human beings as free and equal; Rand, an atheist, grounded them in the biological and psychological requirements of human survival. Since survival requires the use of reason, and reason operates by individual choice (you cannot force someone to think), the conditions necessary for rational thought and action must be protected. Rights, in Rand's framework, are not gifts from God or grants from government but objective requirements of human life.\\n\\nThis biological grounding creates both strengths and problems. The strength is that it provides a secular, naturalistic foundation for rights that does not depend on religious premises or social contract fictions. The problem is the derivation: how do you get from 'humans need to think to survive' to 'taxation is theft' and 'the welfare state is immoral'? Critics have argued that the logical chain involves several leaps. Even if reason is necessary for survival, it does not follow that all forms of collective action or redistributive taxation violate rights. A society could, in principle, tax income to fund public education that enhances the rational capacities of all citizens — which would seem to serve Rand's own standard of value.\\n\\nRand's political philosophy also faced the problem of anarchism. If individual rights are absolute and no collective may violate them, why should there be a government at all? Rand rejected anarcho-capitalism (the view held by some of her followers, notably Murray Rothbard) and argued that government is necessary to protect rights through police, courts, and national defense. But she insisted that government must be funded voluntarily, not through taxation — a position that raises obvious practical difficulties. How would a government funded by voluntary contributions avoid becoming the instrument of its largest donors?\\n\\nThe influence of Rand's rights theory on American politics has been substantial but selective. Politicians and activists who cite Rand typically embrace her defense of property rights and free markets while quietly ignoring her atheism, her support for abortion rights, and her contempt for religious conservatism. This selective appropriation tells us something about how philosophical ideas function in political culture: they are adopted not as complete systems but as rhetorical resources for positions people already hold.\\n\\nThe academic philosophical response to Rand has been largely dismissive, but a few serious engagements exist. The philosopher Tara Smith has produced rigorous defenses of Rand's metaethics and theory of rights within the framework of analytic philosophy. Douglas Rasmussen and Douglas Den Uyl have developed a neo-Aristotelian liberalism that draws on Rand while addressing some of her philosophical weaknesses. Whether Rand's rights theory can survive the transition from popular philosophy to academic rigor remains an open question — but the sheer number of people who have encountered philosophical arguments about rights for the first time through her novels makes her cultural significance independent of the academic verdict." }],`
  },

  // === FRIEDRICH HAYEK ===
  // 1. The Knowledge Problem
  {
    find: `his insight that dispersed knowledge cannot be centralized has influenced fields from computer science to organizational theory." },\n     { title:"Spontaneous Order"`,
    replace: `his insight that dispersed knowledge cannot be centralized has influenced fields from computer science to organizational theory.",
       expanded:"Hayek's knowledge problem argument, first laid out in his 1945 essay 'The Use of Knowledge in Society,' drew on a distinction between different kinds of knowledge that remains underappreciated. Scientific knowledge — the kind that can be written in textbooks and communicated to experts — is only one type. Equally important is what Hayek called 'knowledge of the particular circumstances of time and place': the shipper who knows that an empty cargo ship is available at a particular port, the real estate agent who knows which neighborhood is about to gentrify, the factory foreman who knows which machine tends to overheat on humid days. This knowledge is concrete, local, often fleeting, and impossible to communicate to a central authority in time for it to be useful.\\n\\nMichael Polanyi, working independently, developed a parallel concept: 'tacit knowledge,' the kind of know-how that cannot be fully articulated in words or rules. A skilled craftsman knows how to shape wood in ways that no instruction manual can capture. A experienced doctor diagnoses illness through pattern recognition that resists formalization. Hayek's argument implies that an economy runs on vast quantities of such tacit knowledge, distributed across millions of practitioners, and that any attempt to replace this distributed intelligence with a centralized plan necessarily destroys information.\\n\\nThe price system, in Hayek's analysis, functions as a kind of telecommunications network — transmitting information about scarcity and value across the entire economy in a compressed, impersonal form. When a tin mine collapses in Bolivia, the price of tin rises worldwide, and every user of tin — without knowing anything about the mine collapse — adjusts their behavior: they use less tin, seek substitutes, recycle existing tin products. No central planner could process and distribute this information as quickly or efficiently. The market does it automatically, through the self-interested responses of millions of participants.\\n\\nCritics of Hayek have pointed out that markets also produce systematic failures: they underprovide public goods, generate negative externalities (pollution, financial contagion), and can transmit distorted price signals during speculative bubbles. Hayek acknowledged some of these problems — he was not a market anarchist — but argued that government interventions designed to correct market failures typically create new information problems of their own. The regulator who sets pollution standards faces the same knowledge problem as the central planner: she must determine the optimal level of pollution control for thousands of different industries and locations, using information she does not and cannot possess.\\n\\nThe knowledge problem has found new applications in the age of big data and artificial intelligence. Some have argued that modern computational power resolves Hayek's objection — that algorithms processing vast datasets can now do what central planners of the 1940s could not. Hayek's defenders respond that the problem is not computational capacity but the nature of the knowledge itself: tacit knowledge, entrepreneurial judgment, and the subjective values of millions of consumers cannot be reduced to data points, no matter how powerful the computer processing them." },
     { title:"Spontaneous Order"`
  },
  // 2. Spontaneous Order
  {
    find: `remains central to debates about the proper scope of government intervention." },\n     { title:"The Road to Serfdom", desc:"In his most famous work`,
    replace: `remains central to debates about the proper scope of government intervention.",
       expanded:"The concept of spontaneous order has intellectual roots that predate Hayek. The Scottish Enlightenment thinkers — Adam Smith, Adam Ferguson, and David Hume — had already identified the phenomenon. Ferguson's phrase, 'the result of human action but not of human design,' captured the core idea that Hayek would develop into a systematic theory. Smith's 'invisible hand' is the most famous example: individual actors pursuing their own interests produce, unintentionally, an efficient allocation of resources that no planner could replicate.\\n\\nHayek's contribution was to generalize this insight beyond economics. Language is a spontaneous order: no committee designed English or Mandarin; they evolved through millions of individual speech acts over centuries, producing grammatical structures of astonishing complexity. The common law is a spontaneous order: it emerged from the accumulated decisions of individual judges resolving individual disputes, each building on precedent, and the resulting body of law is more nuanced and adaptable than any legislation a parliament could draft. Scientific knowledge is a spontaneous order: no central authority directs the research agenda of the global scientific community, yet the decentralized efforts of millions of researchers produce a body of knowledge far exceeding what any planned research program could achieve.\\n\\nThe distinction between spontaneous orders and designed organizations is not always sharp, and Hayek's critics have pressed this point. Modern markets operate within legal frameworks created by legislatures. The common law depends on a court system established by political authority. Language evolves spontaneously but is also shaped by dictionaries, grammar books, and educational institutions. The question is not whether spontaneous order exists — it clearly does — but whether it is always superior to deliberate design. Hayek sometimes wrote as if spontaneous processes are inherently wiser than conscious planning, but this is not obviously true: spontaneous orders can also produce path-dependent inefficiencies, entrenched inequalities, and destructive feedback loops.\\n\\nHayek connected spontaneous order to a broader evolutionary epistemology. The institutions that survive and spread — particular legal customs, moral rules, economic practices — do so because they enable the groups that adopt them to thrive. This is cultural evolution: not the survival of the fittest individual but the survival of the fittest set of rules. Hayek's late work, The Fatal Conceit, argued that the extended order of human cooperation (global trade, complex division of labor) rests on rules — respect for property, honesty in exchange, the keeping of promises — that were not invented by anyone but evolved because groups that followed them outcompeted groups that did not.\\n\\nThe influence of Hayek's concept of spontaneous order extends well beyond economics. In computer science, distributed systems and emergent algorithms (such as those used in blockchain technology) embody the principle that complex coordination can arise without central control. In biology, the concept maps onto evolutionary theory and ecosystem dynamics. In urban planning, Jane Jacobs's defense of organic neighborhood development against top-down urban renewal echoes Hayek's argument almost exactly — though Jacobs arrived at her conclusions independently." },
     { title:"The Road to Serfdom", desc:"In his most famous work`
  },
  // 3. The Road to Serfdom
  {
    find: `It remains central to debates about the relationship between economic freedom and political freedom." }],`,
    replace: `It remains central to debates about the relationship between economic freedom and political freedom.",
       expanded:"The Road to Serfdom was written in 1943-44, when Hayek was teaching at the London School of Economics (relocated to Cambridge during the Blitz) and watching the British Labour Party prepare its program for postwar nationalization. The book was dedicated 'to the socialists of all parties' — a pointed reminder that Hayek's target was not Labour specifically but the broader intellectual consensus that central planning was the rational, modern alternative to the chaos of free markets. This consensus was held across the political spectrum: many Conservatives as well as Labour politicians accepted the wartime planned economy as a model for peacetime governance.\\n\\nHayek's argument was structural, not conspiratorial. He did not claim that Clement Attlee or the Fabians were secret totalitarians. His point was that comprehensive economic planning creates institutional pressures that push even well-meaning democrats toward authoritarianism. When the state controls all economic resources, every economic decision becomes a political decision. Who gets steel — the housing ministry or the defense ministry? Which regions receive investment? Which industries are allowed to contract? These questions cannot be resolved by market prices (which have been abolished) and are too numerous and technical for parliamentary debate. They must be delegated to bureaucrats, who thereby acquire discretionary power over the lives of citizens that no democratic mandate authorized.\\n\\nThe empirical record since 1944 has provided evidence for both sides of the debate. The Soviet Union, Maoist China, and the Eastern Bloc confirmed Hayek's prediction that comprehensive central planning and political freedom are incompatible. But the Scandinavian social democracies — which combine extensive welfare states with market economies, democratic governance, and strong civil liberties — present a challenge to any simplistic reading of Hayek's thesis. Hayek himself distinguished between central planning (directing the entire economy from above) and a welfare state (providing a social safety net within a market economy), and he endorsed the latter. Many of his readers have not observed this distinction.\\n\\nThe book's reception history is itself instructive. Academic economists in the 1940s and 1950s largely dismissed it as alarmist polemic. The popular Reader's Digest condensed version reached millions of Americans and made Hayek famous outside academia. By the 1970s, stagflation (the combination of high inflation and high unemployment that Keynesian theory could not explain) and the visible economic failures of planned economies shifted opinion toward Hayek. Margaret Thatcher reportedly slammed a copy of his later work, The Constitution of Liberty, on a table and declared, 'This is what we believe.' The collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991 was widely seen as vindicating Hayek's core argument.\\n\\nThe debate Hayek initiated remains alive in new forms. Contemporary arguments about industrial policy, technology regulation, and responses to climate change all involve the question of how much central direction an economy can absorb before it compromises the dispersed decision-making that makes markets effective. Hayek's contribution was to frame this not as a technical question about efficiency but as a question about power: who decides, and what institutional constraints prevent the decision-makers from becoming tyrants?" }],`
  },

  // === LUDWIG VON MISES ===
  // 1. Economic Calculation Problem
  {
    find: `The debate remains central to political economy and the philosophy of social institutions." },\n     { title:"Praxeology: Economics as the Logic of Human Action"`,
    replace: `The debate remains central to political economy and the philosophy of social institutions.",
       expanded:"Mises published his calculation argument in 1920, just three years after the Bolshevik Revolution, at a time when many intellectuals across Europe regarded socialism as the rational future of economic organization. The argument's logic is deceptively simple. In a market economy, the means of production (factories, raw materials, machinery) are privately owned and traded. These trades generate prices that reflect the relative scarcity and usefulness of different resources. A steel manufacturer deciding whether to produce rails or girders can compare the market prices of both and direct resources toward the more valued product. Under socialism, the state owns all means of production, so there are no genuine market transactions in capital goods — and therefore no prices to guide allocation decisions.\\n\\nThe socialist economists Oskar Lange and Abba Lerner responded in the 1930s with the theory of 'market socialism.' They proposed that a central planning board could simulate market prices by a process of trial and error: set initial prices, observe surpluses and shortages, and adjust prices accordingly. Mises and Hayek argued that this response missed the point. Real market prices are not just numbers assigned by an authority; they emerge from the actual entrepreneurial decisions of people risking their own capital, responding to local knowledge, and making judgments under genuine uncertainty. A simulated price set by a bureaucrat who bears no personal risk and possesses no local knowledge is not a price in the economically relevant sense — it is an administered number that lacks the informational content of a real market price.\\n\\nThe historical evidence has largely supported Mises's prediction, though the interpretation remains contested. Soviet central planners faced exactly the problems Mises described: without genuine prices for capital goods, they could not determine whether it was more efficient to build a bridge from steel or concrete, to transport goods by rail or truck, to invest in heavy industry or consumer goods. They resorted to crude physical planning (tonnage targets, output quotas) that produced spectacular waste — factories producing goods nobody wanted, resources transported thousands of miles when alternatives were available locally. The Soviet economy could copy price structures from Western market economies (and did), but this merely confirmed Mises's point: the information embedded in market prices is generated by market processes and cannot be independently produced by planning.\\n\\nContemporary discussions of the calculation problem have taken new directions. Some economists argue that modern computing power and big data could solve the information problem that defeated Soviet planners. Others point to the success of large corporations — which are themselves internally planned economies, allocating resources by managerial decision rather than market prices — as evidence that planning can work at scale. Mises's defenders respond that corporations operate within a market environment that provides the price signals they use for internal planning, and that firms that grow too large and lose contact with market feedback tend to become inefficient — which is why corporate bureaucracies are periodically disrupted by smaller, more agile competitors.\\n\\nThe calculation argument also has implications beyond economics. Any institution that replaces decentralized, price-guided decision-making with centralized administrative control faces a version of the same problem: how to allocate resources rationally without the informational feedback that markets provide. This applies to healthcare systems, educational bureaucracies, and government agencies — all of which must make allocation decisions without the price signals that would guide a market actor." },
     { title:"Praxeology: Economics as the Logic of Human Action"`
  },
  // 2. Praxeology
  {
    find: `The debate touches fundamental questions about the nature of economic knowledge." },\n     { title:"Liberalism as a Philosophy of Peace and Cooperation"`,
    replace: `The debate touches fundamental questions about the nature of economic knowledge.",
       expanded:"Mises's praxeological method was self-consciously modeled on geometry and formal logic rather than on the empirical sciences. Just as the theorems of geometry follow deductively from axioms and definitions, Mises claimed that the laws of economics follow deductively from the action axiom — the recognition that human beings employ means to achieve chosen ends. The law of marginal utility, for instance, follows from the fact that an actor will always direct the first unit of a good toward the most valued end, the second toward the next most valued end, and so on. This is not an empirical generalization that might be overturned by data; it is a logical implication of the concept of purposeful action.\\n\\nThe methodological contrast with mainstream economics is stark. Since the mid-20th century, economics has increasingly modeled itself on the natural sciences: formulating hypotheses, testing them against statistical data, and revising theories in light of empirical results. Econometrics — the application of statistical methods to economic data — is the dominant tool of professional economics. Mises rejected this entire approach. Human beings, he argued, are not atoms. They act on the basis of subjective values, beliefs, and expectations that change unpredictably. No amount of statistical data about past behavior can yield reliable predictions about future behavior, because human beings can always change their minds, learn new information, or respond to novel circumstances in ways that no model anticipated.\\n\\nMises's methodological position attracted criticism from both mainstream economists and fellow free-market thinkers. Milton Friedman, who shared many of Mises's policy conclusions, argued that the test of an economic theory is not the realism of its assumptions but the accuracy of its predictions — a pragmatic approach that Mises would have regarded as a category error. Karl Popper, whose philosophy of science influenced many Austrian economists, insisted that genuine scientific theories must be falsifiable by empirical evidence — a criterion that praxeological claims, being derived by pure deduction, do not meet.\\n\\nDefenders of praxeology argue that its critics confuse different types of knowledge. Physics discovers contingent regularities in nature — laws that could, in principle, have been otherwise. Praxeology identifies necessary truths about the structure of rational action — truths that hold in any possible world where purposeful beings make choices. The law of marginal utility is not a statistical generalization but a logical truth, like the principle that you cannot have your cake and eat it too. Denying it does not produce an alternative theory; it produces incoherence.\\n\\nThe debate over praxeology illuminates a broader question in the philosophy of social science: what kind of knowledge is possible about human beings? If human action is genuinely purposeful and creative — if people can always surprise us — then the predictive models that work in physics may be the wrong tool for economics. But if pure deduction cannot tell us anything about the specific, contingent features of actual economies (interest rates, unemployment levels, growth patterns), then praxeology may yield truths that are certain but empty. The tension between these positions has not been resolved, and Mises's praxeology remains the most rigorous attempt to build economics on a foundation of logical certainty rather than empirical probability." },
     { title:"Liberalism as a Philosophy of Peace and Cooperation"`
  },
  // 3. Liberalism as a Philosophy of Peace and Cooperation
  {
    find: `His book Liberalism (1927) remains one of the clearest statements of the classical liberal worldview." }],`,
    replace: `His book Liberalism (1927) remains one of the clearest statements of the classical liberal worldview.",
       expanded:"Mises wrote Liberalism in 1927, at a moment when the liberal order of the 19th century was under attack from all directions. Bolshevism had triumphed in Russia. Fascism was consolidating in Italy. Nationalist and protectionist movements were fragmenting the global trading system that had reached its peak before World War I. Many intellectuals regarded liberalism as an exhausted ideology — the creed of the 19th-century bourgeoisie, soon to be swept away by socialism, nationalism, or some combination of both.\\n\\nMises's response was to present liberalism not as a set of policy preferences but as a unified philosophical system. The argument begins with a claim about human diversity: people have different values, different goals, different conceptions of the good life. In a world of scarcity, these differences create the potential for conflict — if I want the same land, the same resources, the same labor that you want, we are potential enemies. Liberalism solves this problem through the institution of private property and voluntary exchange. When property rights are secure and exchange is free, our differences become a source of mutual benefit rather than conflict: I grow wheat, you raise cattle, and we trade — each gaining from the other's specialized skills.\\n\\nThe connection between free trade and peace was central to Mises's argument. He pointed to the 19th-century era of relatively free international trade as a period of relative peace among the great powers, and to the rise of protectionism, autarky, and economic nationalism in the early 20th century as a cause (not merely a symptom) of the two world wars. When nations trade freely, their economies become interdependent, and war becomes economically irrational — you do not bomb your best customer's factories. When nations pursue economic self-sufficiency, foreign trade becomes a zero-sum competition for resources, and the economic motive for peace disappears.\\n\\nCritics from the left have argued that Mises's liberalism ignores the realities of power. In a world of vast inequalities in wealth and bargaining power, 'voluntary exchange' between a landless laborer and a large employer is not truly voluntary — the laborer has no meaningful choice but to accept whatever terms are offered. Marxists contend that private property itself is a form of coercion, since it excludes the majority from resources they need to live. Mises's response was that these criticisms confuse the market economy with the results of previous state interventions (feudalism, colonialism, mercantilism) and that a genuinely free market — which has never fully existed — would distribute opportunity more broadly than any alternative system.\\n\\nMises's liberal vision has a Stoic quality: he did not promise utopia or even happiness, only the absence of coercive conflict. A free society, in his account, is not a society where everyone thrives but a society where the rules of cooperation are fair and voluntary. Whether this minimalist vision is sufficient to sustain a political community — whether people need more from their social order than the opportunity to trade — is the question that communitarians, social democrats, and conservatives have all pressed against the classical liberal tradition that Mises so rigorously articulated." }],`
  },

  // === THOMAS KUHN ===
  // 1. Paradigm Shifts
  {
    find: `Kuhn forced a reckoning with the idea that scientific progress involves social, psychological, and historical forces alongside rational argument." },\n     { title:"Incommensurability of Paradigms"`,
    replace: `Kuhn forced a reckoning with the idea that scientific progress involves social, psychological, and historical forces alongside rational argument.",
       expanded:"Kuhn came to the philosophy of science through an unusual path. Trained as a physicist at Harvard, he was asked in 1947 to teach a course on the history of science for undergraduates as part of Harvard's general education program. Preparing the course forced him to read the original works of scientists like Aristotle, Ptolemy, and Newton, and he was struck by how differently these figures understood the world — not merely in their conclusions but in their basic assumptions about what counted as a scientific question, what counted as evidence, and what counted as a satisfactory explanation. Aristotelian physics was not simply wrong in the way that a student who miscalculates on an exam is wrong; it operated within an entirely different framework of concepts.\\n\\nThis biographical detail matters because it explains why Kuhn's account of science is historical rather than logical. Philosophers like Karl Popper had analyzed science in terms of its logical structure: a scientific theory makes predictions; if the predictions fail, the theory is falsified; a new theory replaces it. Kuhn's reading of history showed that science does not actually work this way. Theories are not abandoned the moment they encounter a counter-instance. Newtonian mechanics faced anomalies for over a century (the precession of Mercury's orbit, for instance) without anyone concluding that Newton was wrong. Scientists treated these as puzzles to be solved within the Newtonian framework, not as refutations of it. Only when anomalies accumulated to the point of crisis — and only when a viable alternative framework was available — did the scientific community shift.\\n\\nThe concept of 'normal science' was itself a provocation. Popper and other rationalist philosophers of science had celebrated science as the epitome of critical thinking — the relentless questioning of established ideas. Kuhn argued that most scientists, most of the time, are not questioning their basic framework at all. They are solving puzzles within it: applying established methods to new problems, extending the paradigm's reach, refining its precision. This is not intellectual laziness; it is functionally necessary. A paradigm is productive only if scientists commit to it deeply enough to develop its full potential. If every anomaly provoked a fundamental rethinking, science would never accumulate the detailed knowledge that makes paradigm shifts possible in the first place.\\n\\nThe phrase 'paradigm shift' itself has had an interesting afterlife. Kuhn used it in a specific, technical sense to describe wholesale changes in the conceptual framework of a scientific discipline. In popular and business usage, it has been diluted to mean any significant change in thinking — a new marketing strategy, a new management philosophy, a new technology. Kuhn was reportedly irritated by this popularization, which stripped his concept of its specific content. In the second edition of The Structure of Scientific Revolutions, he noted that critics had identified over twenty different senses in which he used the word 'paradigm' and attempted to clarify his terminology, replacing 'paradigm' in some contexts with 'disciplinary matrix.'\\n\\nThe lasting significance of Kuhn's account lies in its challenge to a simple progress narrative. If science advances through revolutions rather than accumulation, and if successive paradigms are incommensurable, then it is not obvious that later science is 'closer to the truth' than earlier science. Kuhn himself was ambivalent about this implication — he did not want to be a relativist, and he believed that later paradigms are in some sense better than earlier ones (more precise, more wide-ranging). But he could not specify a paradigm-independent standard by which to measure this improvement, and this unresolved tension has fueled debate in the philosophy of science ever since." },
     { title:"Incommensurability of Paradigms"`
  },
  // 2. Incommensurability
  {
    find: `The debate over incommensurability remains central to philosophy of science." },\n     { title:"Normal Science and the Role of Anomalies"`,
    replace: `The debate over incommensurability remains central to philosophy of science.",
       expanded:"The incommensurability thesis is best understood through specific examples. Consider the concept of 'mass' in Newtonian and Einsteinian physics. In Newton's mechanics, mass is an intrinsic, invariant property of an object — a brick has the same mass whether it is sitting on a table or hurtling through space at high speed. In Einstein's special relativity, mass varies with velocity: as an object approaches the speed of light, its relativistic mass increases without limit. A Newtonian physicist and an Einsteinian physicist using the word 'mass' are not disagreeing about the value of a shared quantity; they are using the same word to refer to different concepts embedded in different theoretical frameworks.\\n\\nThis is not merely a terminological inconvenience. If the meanings of key scientific terms change between paradigms, then the two paradigms cannot be directly compared. You cannot say that Einstein's theory explains everything Newton's theory explains plus additional phenomena, because the two theories do not share a common vocabulary in which such a comparison could be stated. They are, in Kuhn's metaphor, like speakers of different languages — communication is possible but requires translation, and translation always involves some loss or distortion of meaning.\\n\\nThe incommensurability thesis drew fierce criticism. Karl Popper accused Kuhn of making science irrational — of suggesting that paradigm shifts are like religious conversions rather than rational decisions based on evidence. Israel Scheffler argued that incommensurability leads to relativism: if there is no neutral ground from which to compare paradigms, then there is no basis for claiming that one is better than another, and the choice between them becomes arbitrary. Hilary Putnam argued that the very fact that historians of science can describe both Newtonian and Einsteinian physics in a single language (English, or the language of mathematics) shows that the theories are not truly incommensurable.\\n\\nKuhn spent much of his later career refining and narrowing the incommensurability thesis in response to these criticisms. He distinguished between 'local incommensurability' (certain key terms change meaning between paradigms) and 'global incommensurability' (the two paradigms share no common ground at all). He endorsed the former and denied the latter. Two paradigms can share enough vocabulary and enough empirical ground to make comparison possible — but the comparison will always be imperfect, because the core theoretical terms resist exact translation.\\n\\nThe incommensurability debate connects to broader questions in the philosophy of language. If the meaning of a scientific term depends on the theory in which it is embedded (a view called 'meaning holism'), then any change in theory changes the meanings of the terms it uses — and strict comparison across theories becomes impossible. W.V.O. Quine's thesis of the indeterminacy of translation, developed independently, raises similar problems: if there is no unique correct translation between languages, then there is no unique correct comparison between theories expressed in different conceptual frameworks. These are not merely academic puzzles; they bear on practical questions about how to evaluate competing scientific theories, how to teach the history of science, and what it means to say that science gives us knowledge of 'the way the world really is.'" },
     { title:"Normal Science and the Role of Anomalies"`
  },
  // 3. Normal Science and Anomalies
  {
    find: `normal science requires commitment to a paradigm to be productive, but that same commitment creates inertia against change." }],`,
    replace: `normal science requires commitment to a paradigm to be productive, but that same commitment creates inertia against change.",
       expanded:"Kuhn's account of normal science drew on his detailed historical studies of actual scientific practice. In The Copernican Revolution (1957), he traced how Ptolemaic astronomy functioned as a paradigm for over a millennium — not because astronomers were ignorant or dogmatic, but because the Ptolemaic system worked. It predicted the positions of the planets with reasonable accuracy, it provided a framework for calendar-making and navigation, and it was embedded in a broader cosmological picture (Aristotelian physics, Christian theology) that made intellectual sense of the universe. Normal science within the Ptolemaic paradigm consisted of refining the system — adding epicycles, adjusting parameters, extending predictions to new phenomena — all within the basic framework of a stationary Earth at the center of rotating celestial spheres.\\n\\nThe role of anomalies in triggering paradigm shifts is more complex than popular accounts suggest. Kuhn did not claim that a single dramatic refutation overthrows a paradigm. Anomalies are always present — no paradigm perfectly explains every observation — and in normal times they are treated as puzzles rather than refutations. The precession of Mercury's perihelion was known to be anomalous within Newtonian mechanics for decades, but no one took it as a reason to abandon Newton. Astronomers assumed the anomaly would eventually be explained by some undiscovered factor (a hidden planet, perhaps). It was only after Einstein's general relativity offered an alternative framework that also explained the Mercury anomaly that the anomaly was retrospectively recognized as a genuine refutation of Newton.\\n\\nThis raises a difficult question about rationality in science. If anomalies are not treated as refutations until an alternative paradigm is available, then the decision to maintain or abandon a paradigm cannot be purely evidence-driven. It depends on what alternatives are on offer. A scientist in 1850 who rejected Newtonian mechanics because of the Mercury anomaly would have had nothing to replace it with — and would have been rightly regarded as reckless. A scientist in 1920 who clung to Newton despite the availability of general relativity would have been displaying a different kind of irrationality. The rationality of scientific belief depends not just on the evidence but on the available alternatives — a context-sensitive judgment that resists reduction to formal rules.\\n\\nMax Planck's observation that science advances 'one funeral at a time' — meaning that older scientists never fully accept new paradigms and that change comes only as new generations take their place — was important to Kuhn's account. It suggests that paradigm shifts are not purely intellectual events but generational ones. Younger scientists, who have not invested decades of work in the old paradigm and who learned the new framework during their training, find the shift natural. Older scientists, whose entire careers were built within the old paradigm and whose professional identities are tied to it, resist — not from stupidity but from a rational attachment to the framework that made their work possible.\\n\\nKuhn's description of normal science has practical implications for how scientific institutions are organized. If most productive science consists of detailed puzzle-solving within an established framework, then scientific training should emphasize mastery of the current paradigm — its methods, its assumptions, its unsolved problems — rather than encouraging premature questioning of fundamentals. This is, in fact, how most graduate programs in science work: students learn to do research within the existing framework long before they are in a position to challenge it. Kuhn's account explains why this conservative training model is functional rather than merely authoritarian." }],`
  },

  // === EDMUND GETTIER ===
  // 1. The Gettier Cases
  {
    find: `This three-page paper generated more philosophical literature than works a hundred times its length." },\n     { title:"The Problem of Epistemic Luck"`,
    replace: `This three-page paper generated more philosophical literature than works a hundred times its length.",
       expanded:"The Gettier cases need to be understood in the context of mid-20th-century epistemology. By the early 1960s, the 'justified true belief' (JTB) analysis of knowledge had become so widely accepted that it was treated as a starting point rather than a thesis requiring defense. Textbooks presented it as the standard definition. The few philosophers who discussed it typically did so in order to analyze the individual components — what counts as justification? what is the nature of belief? — rather than to question the analysis itself. Gettier's paper arrived like a cold splash of water.\\n\\nThe structure of a Gettier case has three essential features. First, the subject forms a belief through a reliable process of reasoning — the belief is genuinely justified. Second, the belief happens to be true. Third, the truth of the belief is disconnected from the justification — the belief is true, but not for the reasons the subject thinks. Smith's justified belief that 'the man who will get the job has ten coins in his pocket' is true because Smith himself will get the job and happens to have ten coins — not because Jones, whom Smith's evidence points to, has ten coins. The justification and the truth are, so to speak, ships passing in the night.\\n\\nGettier's original examples have been supplemented by hundreds of variations, many more vivid and compelling. In one famous case: you are driving through the countryside and see what appears to be a barn. You form the justified true belief that 'there is a barn in that field.' But unbeknownst to you, the entire area is filled with convincing barn facades — fake barns that look real from the road. The one you happen to be looking at is the only real barn in the county. Your belief is justified (it looks exactly like a barn) and true (it is a barn), but it seems clear that you do not know there is a barn there. You got lucky.\\n\\nThe reason Gettier cases are so philosophically significant is that they seem to show something about the very structure of knowledge. It is not enough for your belief to be true and for you to have good reasons. Your reasons must be appropriately connected to the truth — they must be the right reasons, connected to the right truth-makers, in the right way. But specifying what 'the right way' means has proved extraordinarily difficult, and every proposed specification has generated its own counterexamples.\\n\\nThe paper's impact is all the more striking given its brevity and Gettier's own career. The entire argument occupies fewer than three pages, with no footnotes, no elaborate philosophical apparatus, and only two counterexamples. Gettier reportedly wrote it under pressure to publish something for tenure, had little personal interest in the problem, and published virtually nothing else in his entire career. He was evidently bemused by the attention the paper received. The lesson is that in philosophy, a single well-placed insight can outweigh volumes of systematic theorizing." },
     { title:"The Problem of Epistemic Luck"`
  },
  // 2. Problem of Epistemic Luck
  {
    find: `what distinguishes genuine cognitive achievement from fortunate guessing." },\n     { title:"The Fourth Condition Problem"`,
    replace: `what distinguishes genuine cognitive achievement from fortunate guessing.",
       expanded:"The concept of epistemic luck, though implicit in Gettier's original paper, was developed into a systematic topic by later epistemologists — particularly Duncan Pritchard, whose 2005 book Epistemic Luck provided a taxonomy of the different ways luck can infect the relationship between belief and truth. Not all epistemic luck is problematic. It is a matter of luck that you were born in a time and place where you have access to education, libraries, and scientific knowledge — but this kind of 'evidential luck' does not undermine your knowledge. The luck that matters in Gettier cases is what Pritchard calls 'veritic luck': cases where it is a matter of luck, given the way the belief was formed, that it turns out to be true.\\n\\nThe anti-luck condition on knowledge can be stated informally: you know that p only if it is not a matter of luck that your belief that p is true. But formalizing this intuition has proved difficult. One approach is the 'safety' condition: your belief is safe if, in all nearby possible worlds where you form the belief in the same way, the belief is true. In the barn facade case, your belief is unsafe because in most nearby possible worlds (where you are looking at a facade rather than the one real barn), your belief would be false. Another approach is the 'sensitivity' condition: your belief is sensitive if, had p been false, you would not have believed it. In the barn case, had there been no barn (just another facade), you would still have believed there was a barn — so your belief is insensitive.\\n\\nBoth conditions face counterexamples. The sensitivity condition, developed by Robert Nozick, produces the wrong verdicts in cases involving necessary truths (you cannot fail to believe a mathematical truth is true, since it could not have been false) and in cases where the method of belief-formation is reliable in actual circumstances but not in counterfactual ones. The safety condition struggles with cases where the nearby possible worlds are difficult to specify — how 'nearby' must a possible world be to count?\\n\\nThe concept of epistemic luck also connects to virtue epistemology — the view that knowledge is a kind of cognitive achievement, analogous to an athletic achievement. Just as a basketball shot is not a genuine achievement if the ball goes in by a lucky gust of wind, a true belief is not knowledge if it is true by epistemic luck rather than by the exercise of intellectual skill. Ernest Sosa, John Greco, and other virtue epistemologists have argued that the Gettier problem is best solved not by adding conditions to the JTB analysis but by reconceiving knowledge as apt belief — belief that is true because of (not merely alongside) the believer's cognitive competence.\\n\\nThe epistemic luck framework has been applied beyond traditional epistemology. In legal theory, the concept illuminates questions about the difference between knowledge and reasonable belief in evidentiary standards. In ethics, 'moral luck' — the phenomenon where moral judgments depend on factors beyond the agent's control — raises parallel puzzles about the relationship between responsibility and fortune. The structural similarities between epistemic luck and moral luck suggest that the problem Gettier identified may be an instance of a more general philosophical difficulty with the role of chance in human affairs." },
     { title:"The Fourth Condition Problem"`
  },
  // 3. The Fourth Condition Problem
  {
    find: `The Gettier problem thus became a test case for the methodology of analytic philosophy itself." }],`,
    replace: `The Gettier problem thus became a test case for the methodology of analytic philosophy itself.",
       expanded:"The parade of failed fourth conditions is instructive, because each failure reveals something new about the structure of knowledge. The 'no false lemmas' condition — the idea that knowledge is justified true belief that does not depend on any false assumption — was an early and intuitive response. In Gettier's original case, Smith's reasoning passes through the false assumption that Jones will get the job. Remove that false step, and the Gettier problem disappears. But counterexamples soon emerged in which the subject's reasoning involves no false lemmas at all. In some cases, the subject reasons correctly from true premises and arrives at a true conclusion, but the truth of the conclusion is still accidentally related to the justification.\\n\\nReliabilism — the view proposed by Alvin Goldman that knowledge is true belief produced by a reliable cognitive process — seemed to avoid the Gettier problem by shifting attention from the subject's reasons to the causal mechanism of belief-formation. A process is reliable if it tends to produce true beliefs: perception in good conditions is reliable; guessing is not. But reliabilism faces its own version of the Gettier problem. In the barn facade county, your perceptual process is locally unreliable (most barn-shaped objects in this county are fakes) even though it is globally reliable (perception generally works well). Whether your belief counts as knowledge depends on how we define the relevant reference class — and there is no non-arbitrary way to make this decision. This is the 'generality problem' for reliabilism, and it remains unsolved.\\n\\nThe sensitivity and safety conditions (discussed under the epistemic luck heading) represent attempts to capture the anti-luck intuition in modal terms — knowledge requires that the belief be connected to the truth not just in the actual world but across a range of possible scenarios. These conditions have the advantage of precision, since possible-worlds semantics provides a well-understood formal framework. But their disadvantage is that they generate counterintuitive verdicts in many cases and are difficult to apply to everyday knowledge attributions. Most ordinary people, when asked whether they know that their car is parked where they left it, do not consider the range of possible worlds in which it might have been towed.\\n\\nSome philosophers have drawn a more radical conclusion: knowledge simply cannot be analyzed into necessary and sufficient conditions. Timothy Williamson has argued that knowledge is a primitive — a fundamental mental state that cannot be broken down into belief plus additional ingredients. On this view, the entire post-Gettier research program rests on a mistaken assumption: that knowledge is a composite concept susceptible to analysis. Williamson proposes reversing the traditional priority: instead of analyzing knowledge in terms of belief, we should understand belief in terms of knowledge (belief is the broader category that includes both knowledge and mere opinion).\\n\\nThe failure of the fourth-condition project has also prompted reflection on the method of conceptual analysis itself. The method assumes that concepts like 'knowledge' have precise boundaries that can be captured by necessary and sufficient conditions — and that counterexamples reveal the true boundaries. But if concepts are 'cluster' or 'family resemblance' concepts (as Wittgenstein argued many concepts are), then no set of conditions will capture all and only the genuine cases. The Gettier problem may persist not because epistemologists are insufficiently clever but because the concept of knowledge is structured in a way that resists the kind of analysis they are attempting." }],`
  }
];

